The '''black-winged snowfinch''' or '''Adams's snowfinch''' ('''''Montifringilla adamsi'''''),<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=g_3QDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA15 |page=15 |isbn=978-1-4729-8269-8 | title=The Eponym Dictionary of Birds | date=19 March 2020 | publisher=Bloomsbury }}</ref> is a species of [[bird]] in the [[Old World sparrow|sparrow]] family.

It is found in China, India, Nepal, and Pakistan. Its natural [[habitat]] is subtropical or tropical dry [[shrubland]]. It is commonly resident in the Tibetan plateau region of north-western Nepal, where it spends the summer at elevations of {{convert|4200|–|5100|m|ft}} and the winter at {{convert|2530|–|3445|m|ft}}, on open stony hillsides, on plateau and near villages.<ref name="GII">{{cite book|last=Grimmett|first=Richard|author2=Inskipp, Carol |author3= Inskipp, Tim  |year=2000|title=Birds of Nepal|publisher=Christopher Helm Ltd.|location=London|isbn=0-7136-5166-0}}</ref>

